article.headline: After 17 months of waiting, Catchings proves her worth
article.linkText: Finally: Catchings makes memorable debut as Fever beat Shock
article.story: INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings waited nearly 17 months to make her WNBA debut, so what were a few more hours? As she arrived at Conseco Fieldhouse for the shootaround, she felt nervous and wondered if she could give the fans a glimpse of how she played in college. ``I couldn't wait for the game start. I had to get out there,'' she said. Once she did, she took over. Catchings had 23 points and 13 rebounds, and Nikki McCray and Alicia Thompson added 16 points as the Fever beat the Detroit Shock 79-62 Saturday night. Catchings, the third overall pick in last year's draft, played her first regular-season game since tearing the anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee in January 2001 while at Tennessee. She reinjured the knee during a Fever practice in Houston last July, ending any hopes of an early return. Her pregame jitters quickly disappeared after tipoff. ``After that ball went up, nothing else mattered,'' Catchings said. ``It felt really good out there.'' The Fever opened the season barely resembling last year's team that tied with three other teams for the worst record in the WNBA at 10-22. Catchings and McCray, acquired in an offseason deal with Washington, have led an up-tempo, fast-breaking offense, a defensive-toughness and some optimism to what has been one of the worst teams in the league. The Fever forced 18 turnovers, held the Shock (0-2) to 37 percent shooting and had a 40-25 rebounding advantage. Deanna Nolan led Detroit with 15 points and Swin Cash had 13. Catchings had a steal on Detroit's first possession and turned it into a fast-break layup. She hit a 3 for Indiana's first double-digit lead and went 7-for-10 overall in the half. In the final minute of the half, she dribbled through a double team, then brought the ball just over the outstretched hand of a low-post defender for another basket. Catchings and McCray, both former Tennessee standouts, helped Indiana to a 13-point lead in the first half. Two 3-pointers by Nolan and one by Begona Garcia pulled the Shock to 47-46 early in the second, but the they could never take the lead. ``Maybe this team would have folded last year, but this year we stayed focused and stuck with it,'' McCray said. The Fever have combined for 19 wins their first two years and have only been over .500 one other time (2-1 in 2000) in team history. Now they're talking about contending for the playoffs and Catchings is leading the way. ``There are some things I used to be able to do that I haven't perfected yet,'' she said. ``With a little more playing time, I'll get it down. My goal is to be better than I was before.''
